{# Introduction Section #}
<section class="section">
  <div class="content-container">
    <h2 class="section-title">What Is Humanist Modernism?</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <p class="text-body leading-[1.7] text-text-primary">
        Humanist Modernism emerged as a thoughtful response to the cold precision of early modernist
        design. While honoring the clarity and rational structure of Swiss Design, it prioritizes
        human readability, emotional warmth, and cognitive comfort above geometric perfection.
      </p>

      <p class="text-body leading-[1.7] text-text-primary">
        This approach combines the best of two worlds: the systematic thinking and visual order of
        modernism with the accessible, human-centered principles that make design truly serve its
        audience. The result is communication that feels both sophisticated and approachable.
      </p>
    </div>

    <blockquote class="pull-quote">
      "Design is not just what it looks like and feels like. Design is how it works."
      <cite class="quote-attribution">— Steve Jobs</cite>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
</section>

{# Visual Characteristics #}
<section class="section bg-bg-secondary">
  <div class="max-w-measure-wide mx-auto px-[12%]">
    <h2 class="section-title">Visual Characteristics</h2>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-2xl mt-2xl">
      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="text-h3 font-semibold mb-md text-text-primary">Typography</h3>
        <p class="text-body leading-[1.7] text-text-secondary">
          Humanist sans-serif typefaces like Frutiger, Open Sans, and Avenir feature calligraphic
          origins, varied stroke widths, and open apertures. Body text sized at 19-21px with 1.6-1.8
          line-height ensures comfortable extended reading.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="text-h3 font-semibold mb-md text-text-primary">Color Palette</h3>
        <p class="text-body leading-[1.7] text-text-secondary">
          Warm neutrals replace stark contrasts. Off-black text (#333) on warm off-white backgrounds
          (#FAFAFA) reduces eye strain while maintaining excellent readability. Accent colors are
          muted and sophisticated.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="text-h3 font-semibold mb-md text-text-primary">Layout & Spacing</h3>
        <p class="text-body leading-[1.7] text-text-secondary">
          Content-first layouts feature single-column text blocks with optimal line lengths (60-75
          characters). Wide margins—10-15% of viewport—create comfortable reading zones. Generous
          vertical rhythm establishes clear visual hierarchy.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3 class="text-h3 font-semibold mb-md text-text-primary">Reading Experience</h3>
        <p class="text-body leading-[1.7] text-text-secondary">
          Frequent subheadings break up long text. Pull quotes highlight key ideas. Lists and
          bullets aid scanning. Ample white space prevents cognitive overload. Every element serves
          the reader's comprehension and comfort.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

